english:
  title: 'A Discourse on Ministers: Farewell to Governor Lee''s Return to His Province'
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    An ancient saying tells us: "To serve as a minister is no easy task." How then can we be anything but vigilant? Though a minister may win the favor of his sovereign, if he loses the trust of his people, he may amass titles and wealth, yet cannot escape their resentment. Though he may earn praise in his own time, if posterity condemns him, he may accomplish great deeds, yet cannot avoid their censure. The ministers of old would rather lose their sovereign's favor than dare incur the people's hatred—they did not rush after status and stipend. They would rather forego present acclaim than dare invite future blame—they did not calculate their achievements. Yet when a man courts resentment and invites censure while chasing only titles, wealth, and deeds, he has already abandoned the way of true service. How much more so when neither riches nor great accomplishments can be assured?

    Consider the types of ministers: There are the weighty ministers and the power-wielding ministers; the loyal ministers and the upright ministers; the treacherous and the base. The weighty minister—I know well what he is. When the sovereign is young and the realm endangered, when the people's will wavers and sudden crisis strikes, when danger looms and doubt clouds all—then the weighty minister stands firm and resolute, holding fast to principle, upholding the great way, caring not for life or death, fortune or calamity for himself alone. Through him the people find peace and affairs find resolution. The ancients knew such men: Yi Yin, the Duke of Zhou, Chen Ping, and Zhou Bo.

    The power-wielding minister is otherwise. He uses circumstances to build his own faction, grasps the sovereign to gain favor, secretly twists the handle of authority and coerces his lord. Though people seethe with resentment, they dare not speak. He too can quiet the tumult of his time, yet compared to the weighty minister, his form resembles but his spirit differs—the gulf between them is as vast as heaven and earth. Thus the ancients spoke of this.

    As for the loyal minister: he forgets his home in service to the realm, forgets his private interest in service to the public good. When his sovereign grieves, he bears humiliation; when his sovereign is shamed, he accepts death. Courageously he acts, caring nothing for himself, following only righteous principle. Such men existed in antiquity—Ji Xin of Han, who died in his sovereign's stead, and Ji Zhao of Jin, whose blood stained his lord's robes.

    The treacherous minister is the reverse. With honeyed words and cunning smile, with schemes and deceptions, he dupes his sovereign and mocks his people. Profit flows to himself; blame flows to his lord. When sudden crisis comes, he pushes his sovereign forward and himself back, even casting stones from behind. Such a man, though his hand never directly strikes, stands but one step from the assassin's blade—he cannot escape the stern judgment of history's recorder.

    What then is the upright minister? When his sovereign errs, he remonstrates with strength. When affairs lack completion, he speaks truth plainly. He fears only that his lord might fall into unrighteousness; he grieves only that his people might suffer innocent death. Without hesitation or retreat he speaks what is right, continuing even unto death. Such men were Long Fang and Bi Gan.

    The base minister stands opposed. He abandons the great way and leaves the righteous path. Through countless schemes and shifting alliances he seeks favor, sparing no degradation. When calamity strikes and chaos follows, it brings ruin in its wake. All flatterers and greedy sycophants are of this ilk. Yet unless the sovereign himself is wise in judgment and open in listening—able to love while knowing hate, to hate while knowing beauty—he may well mistake the loyal and upright for traitors, and traitors for loyal ministers. Emperor Dezong of Tang once said: "People call Lu Chi treacherous, yet I see only his gentle charm." Thus they identified the very source of his treachery. Whether in ancient times or now, a nation's flourishing or decline, a people's wellbeing or suffering—all may be discerned from such observation.

    Alas, how unequal are talents among men! Success and failure alternate, advance and retreat follow one upon the other. Yet all depends upon what the sovereign himself values. Thus Guan Zhong made Qi great, Wei Zheng brought Tang to splendor. The deeds of bold ministers redeemed their faults; the flattery of Pei Ju transformed into loyal service. Is this not the fruit of what was honored?

    Each time I read the records of such matters, my heart is stirred. My friend Li Jun of Yongzhou is a man of simple character, unadorned in manner, unchanging whether times are smooth or perilous. Though he dare not compare himself to the weighty ministers of old, he would not place himself below the truly loyal. He regards the ways of flatterers as beneath contempt. Yet misfortune has followed him—three sovereigns he has served, yet never found occasion to unfold his gifts. Now, as our new sovereign prepares to journey to his province, and the time of departure draws near, the ruler has chosen from his attendants, commanding Li Jun to go before and explain to the people the meaning of this renewal, to comfort their awakening hopes.

    All who have companied with Li Jun have composed verses and asked me to write the opening words. So I have written this Discourse on Ministers to encourage him. And I ask him this: "Our people stretch their necks in yearning for the new sovereign; they open their eyes wide in hope for new governance, as one parched with hunger and thirst awaits food and drink. Will you labor to enrich your stipend and multiply your deeds? Or will you labor for something else? Our hope for you lies not here, but there. Can you not be vigilant in this?"
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Yin served the founding emperor of Han and famously sacrificed his life by impersonating the emperor to allow his lord's escape from mortal danger.
  - key: ''
    value: Ji Zhao of Jin died shielding Emperor Wu from assassins, his blood soaking the emperor's robes, which were thereafter preserved as a memorial.
  - key: ''
    value: Dong Hu was a Spring and Autumn era historian whose name became synonymous with unflinching moral judgment, even recording indirect wrongs against one's sovereign.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three sovereigns' refers to successive rulers of the Korean realm whom Lee Jun served without opportunity to fully realize his potential.
